* IAM allows to manage users and their level of access to the console. It gives:
* centralized access to AWS account.
* Shared access to AWS account.
* Granular permissions.
* Identity Federation like link to Facebook, LinkedIn, etc.,
* Multifactor Authentication.
* Provides temporary access to users/devices.

* Users
* Groups (collection of users under one set of permissions)
* Roles (are created and then assign to AWS resources)
* Policies (apply policies/permisions to a user or group)

* IAM service does not require region selection. The users/Groups/roles/etc., once created, they are available across the world.
* Root account is the email account that used for signup.
